               <msContents>
                  <summary>I) Maṣḥafa lǝdätu la-ʾabuna Takla Hāymānot “Book of the Genealogy of
                     Takla Haymanot” (fols. 3ra-6vb)&#xD; - Genealogy of Takla Hāymānot (fols.
                     3ra-6vb) &#xD; II) Gadla Takla Hāymānot “Vita of Takla Haymanot” (fols.
                     7ra-79va) &#xD; III) Taʾāmra Takla Hāymānot “Miracles of Takla Haymanot”: 12
                     miracles (fols. 79vb-86vb).</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1">

                     <incipit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en"/>
                     </incipit>
                     <explicit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en"/>
                     </explicit>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
                  <!--The data in the items below refers to other items. please remove this items and move the information to the appropriate place.-->
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i2">
                     <note>The text of the Vita has some characteristics of the so-called "Ḥayq
                        recension" of Gadla Takla Hāymānot. Cp. Mss. EMML n<locus target="#1834">1834</locus> (EMML V, 310-14); BN, Éth. 342 (GrébGriaule II, 18-20),
                        Ṭānāsee 162 (SixTana III, 202-06). For a (rough) French translation of the
                        text s. J. DUCHESNE-FOURNET, Mission en Éthiopie, 1<ref type="mss" corresp="ES901190">901-190</ref>3, vol. 1, Paris 1908,<ref type="mss" corresp="ES340431">340-431</ref>. In this case, the text was possibly
                        copied from<ref type="mss" corresp="ESmr036">MR-036</ref>.</note>
                     <note/>
                     <note>The genealogy of Ṣaggā Za-ʾAb, father of St Takla Hāymānot, is left
                        unfinished <locus target="#11ra">11ra-</locus>rb), with remaining part of
                           <locus target="#11rb">11rb</locus> and <locus target="#11v">11v</locus>
                        blank.</note>
                     <note/>
                     <note>The Miracles are part of the cycle connected with the translation of the
                        relics of St Takla Hāymānot.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
